      'The writer creates a powerful sense of danger through carefully chosen language techniques. The verb "screamed" personifies the wind, giving it a violent, almost human quality that immediately establishes threat. This is reinforced by the active verb "hurling," which suggests aggressive, uncontrollable force.\n\nThe use of the semantic field of predation — "predatory," "beast," "slumbering" — creates an extended metaphor suggesting the house itself is a living, dangerous creature. The simile comparing shadows to "the ribs of some vast, slumbering beast" is particularly effective because "slumbering" implies the danger is dormant but could awaken at any moment, building suspense.\n\nThe writer also employs sensory language to heighten the threat. The "acrid stench of smoke" appeals to the sense of smell, while the phrase "something ancient" implies a timeless, unknowable evil. The physical description of Maria\'s "white-knuckled" fingers conveys her terror through bodily response rather than direct statement.\n\nFinally, the paradox of "the silence that was somehow worse than any sound" creates an unsettling atmosphere, suggesting the real danger lies in what is unseen and unheard, which is arguably more frightening than an explicit threat.',
