      "The writer structures the text to build tension gradually, moving from apparent safety to imminent danger.\n\nAt the opening, the writer focuses attention on the domestic setting, creating a false sense of security. Short, declarative sentences establish normality, encouraging the reader to feel settled. This structural choice is important because it makes the shift to danger more shocking.\n\nAs the source develops, the writer introduces the storm through a shift in focus — moving from interior to exterior. The transition is marked by longer, more complex sentences that mirror the growing chaos. This structural shift forces the reader to re-evaluate the safety of the setting, creating tension through contrast.\n\nThe writer uses a narrowing perspective, zooming from the wide landscape to the hallway to Maria's individual body (her fingers on the handle). This funnelling effect creates claustrophobia and intensifies the reader's engagement with Maria's fear. It also mirrors how danger closes in.\n\nFinally, the ending is structured around a paradox — silence replacing sound. This structural reversal (from noise to quiet) subverts the reader's expectations and leaves the text on an unresolved note, compelling the reader to continue. The cyclical return to stillness after chaos creates an unsettling sense that the worst is yet to come.",
