    question:
      'A student said: "The writer makes the reader feel genuinely afraid for Maria\'s safety. The danger feels very real."\n\nTo what extent do you agree?\n\nIn your response, you could:\n- consider your own impressions of the extract\n- evaluate how the writer has created these impressions\n- support your opinions with references to the text',
    modelAnswer:
      'I strongly agree that the writer makes the reader feel genuinely afraid for Maria. The danger is made to feel visceral and immediate through a combination of language, structure, and carefully managed suspense.\n\nThe writer\'s use of personification throughout — the wind "screamed," shadows that "breathe" — transforms the environment into an active antagonist. This is effective because it means Maria is not simply in a storm; she is surrounded by hostile forces. The reader feels her vulnerability because the danger comes from every direction, not a single identifiable source.\n\nFurthermore, the sensory detail creates a physical reading experience. The "acrid stench" and "shards of ice" engage smell and touch, making the reader experience the scene rather than simply observe it. This immersive quality is what makes the fear feel "genuine" rather than literary — it bypasses intellectual engagement and creates a gut response.\n\nHowever, one could argue that the extended metaphor of the "slumbering beast" is slightly overwrought. The accumulation of threatening imagery — smoke, shadows, ice, silence — borders on excess, which could undermine the realism the student identifies. A more restrained approach might actually be more frightening.\n\nDespite this, the final image of Maria listening to silence is masterfully handled. The paradox works because it places the reader in the same position as Maria: waiting, uncertain, vulnerable. This shared experience is the writer\'s most powerful tool for creating genuine fear.\n\nOverall, I largely agree with the student\'s view. While the imagery occasionally risks melodrama, the structural control and sensory precision create a convincingly dangerous atmosphere that makes the reader genuinely concerned for Maria.',
