      "Write a description suggested by this picture: [An abandoned library with sunlight streaming through broken windows, illuminating dust motes floating in the air. Shelves of books stretch into shadow.]\n\nOR\n\nWrite the opening of a story about a moment of discovery.\n\n(24 marks for content and organisation, 16 marks for technical accuracy)",
    modelAnswer:
      'The dust had its own language here.\n\nIt spoke in spirals, each mote a syllable caught in the cathedral light that fell through the broken windows. The sun — indifferent to the ruin it illuminated — drew golden columns through the air, and in those columns the dust performed its slow, endless liturgy. Rising. Turning. Falling. Rising again.\n\nI stood at the threshold and breathed it in: the sweet decay of paper, the mineral tang of crumbled plaster, the ghost of leather bindings that had once held worlds together. My footsteps on the marble floor sent small detonations of sound through the silence, each echo finding the far wall and returning to me changed, softer, as if the building were learning to absorb my presence.\n\nThe shelves stretched before me like the ribcage of some magnificent fallen creature. They rose three storeys, their upper reaches lost in shadow, and they held their books the way a river holds stones — patiently, without effort, as something natural and inevitable. Some volumes had tumbled from their places and lay open on the floor, their pages splayed like wings of birds that had forgotten how to fly.\n\nI picked one up. The cover was the colour of dried blood, embossed with gold that had faded to whisper. Inside, the handwriting was small, precise, and entirely in a language I could not read. But the diagrams needed no translation: constellations, mapped with extraordinary accuracy, each star connected to the next by lines so fine they seemed drawn with a single hair.\n\nThis was not a library. This was an observatory of the mind, a place where someone had charted not the sky above but the sky within. And as I turned the pages, I understood — with the slow, spreading certainty of dawn — that whoever had written this had been looking for exactly what I had come here to find.',
