      "The two sources present starkly different attitudes to education, reflecting their respective time periods.\n\nSource A presents education as a universal entitlement, emphasising that it should be \"accessible to all regardless of background.\" This inclusive approach contrasts sharply with Source B, where education is framed as an exercise in \"discipline\" and \"duty,\" suggesting it is not about access but about compliance and moral formation.\n\nFurthermore, Source A values emotional and personal development, with schools judged on \"pastoral care\" and \"nurturing the whole child.\" Source B explicitly rejects this, stating that \"sentiment has no place\" in education. Where Source A encourages students to \"find their voice,\" Source B uses the metaphor of the \"master's rod\" to suggest that the student's role is to be shaped, not heard.\n\nThe language itself reveals the contrast: Source A uses warm, progressive vocabulary (\"nurture,\" \"inclusivity,\" \"encouraged\"), while Source B employs industrial and military metaphors (\"forged,\" \"discipline\"), presenting education as something done to children rather than for them.",
