    modelAnswer:
      'The writer uses forceful, authoritarian language to present education as a system of control and moral discipline.\n\nThe declarative statement "The business of the schoolroom is discipline" establishes education as transactional and functional through the noun "business." This word choice strips learning of any emotional or intellectual pleasure, framing it instead as a commercial or industrial process. The writer\'s authority is reinforced by the absolute tone — there is no qualification or hedging, reflecting the certainty of Victorian moral values.\n\nThe antithesis between "pleasure" and "duty" explicitly rejects the idea that education should be enjoyable. The writer positions these as mutually exclusive, using the phrase "not for... but for" to create a rigid binary. This rhetorical structure leaves no room for compromise, mirroring the inflexible approach to education being advocated.\n\nThe metaphor of the "master\'s rod" functions both literally and figuratively. Literally, it refers to corporal punishment; figuratively, it represents the authority of the teacher, which the writer considers "as essential... as the blackboard." This comparison elevates punishment to the same status as learning itself, revealing the writer\'s belief that obedience is as important as knowledge.\n\nFinally, the verb "forged" in "character is being forged" draws on the semantic field of metalwork, presenting children as raw material to be hammered into shape. This dehumanising metaphor suggests education is a violent, transformative process in which the child\'s individual identity is secondary to the finished product.',
