      "For this question, refer to both Source A and Source B.\n\nCompare how the two writers convey their different attitudes to education.\n\nIn your answer, you could:\n- compare their different attitudes\n- compare the methods they use to convey their attitudes\n- support your response with references to both texts",
    modelAnswer:
      'Both writers feel passionately about education, but their attitudes could not be more different. Source A presents education as liberation; Source B presents it as subjugation.\n\nThe most fundamental difference lies in who education serves. Source A\'s writer sees education as serving the child: schools should "nurture the whole child" and help students "find their voice." The vocabulary of care — "pastoral," "nurture," "encouraged" — positions the teacher as a guardian. In stark contrast, Source B\'s writer sees education as serving society: children are raw material to be "forged" into useful citizens. The teacher is not a nurturer but a "master," a word that implies ownership and absolute authority.\n\nBoth writers use metaphor, but to opposite effect. Source A\'s metaphor of "finding a voice" is empowering, suggesting self-expression and identity. Source B\'s metaphor of "forging character" is industrial, evoking heat, force, and the erasure of individual shape. Where Source A celebrates individuality, Source B deliberately suppresses it.\n\nThe tone of each piece also reveals their contrasting attitudes. Source A adopts a measured, inclusive register: "accessible to all regardless of background." The writer anticipates and pre-empts objections through reasonable, universal language. Source B, however, employs a commanding, absolutist tone: "Sentiment has no place." The use of the abstract noun "sentiment" dismisses emotion with a single word, while the emphatic negative construction ("has no place") shuts down debate entirely.\n\nStructurally, Source A builds its argument through accumulation — listing the qualities of good education (inclusivity, pastoral care, voice). This creates a sense of abundance and possibility. Source B uses binary opposition (pleasure/duty, rod/blackboard) to create a rigid, hierarchical worldview where there is only right and wrong, obedience and rebellion.\n\nUltimately, the two sources are products of their time. Source A reflects post-war liberal educational values; Source B reflects Victorian utilitarianism. But both are persuasive in their own terms, and the comparison reveals how much our understanding of childhood and learning has transformed.',
