      '"School uniforms crush individuality and should be abolished."\n\nWrite an article for a broadsheet newspaper in which you argue for or against this statement.\n\n(24 marks for content and organisation, 16 marks for technical accuracy)',
    modelAnswer:
      "THE GREAT UNIFORM DEBATE: WHY WHAT YOU WEAR DOESN'T DEFINE WHO YOU ARE\n\nEvery September, the same tired argument surfaces in opinion columns and parent forums across the country: school uniforms are oppressive, outdated, and an affront to personal expression. It is an argument that sounds compelling until you examine it with any rigour.\n\nLet us begin with the central claim — that uniforms \"crush individuality.\" This assumes that identity is located in clothing, that a teenager cannot be creative, rebellious, or unique unless they are wearing the right trainers. It is a strangely consumerist definition of selfhood. True individuality lives in what you think, say, and create — not in what you buy. If anything, uniforms liberate students from the tyranny of fashion, freeing them to be defined by their character rather than their wardrobe.\n\nConsider, too, the social reality of a school without uniforms. Research from the Education Policy Institute consistently demonstrates that non-uniform schools see higher rates of bullying related to appearance and socioeconomic status. When every student wears the same blazer, the child whose parents cannot afford designer brands is indistinguishable from the child whose parents can. The uniform is, in this sense, profoundly egalitarian.\n\nCritics will counter that schools should teach children to navigate the real world, where people dress differently and must learn tolerance. This is a fair point — but it ignores the fact that school is not the real world. It is a controlled environment designed to provide safety and structure while young minds develop. We do not give children complete freedom in any other area of school life — we set curricula, enforce behaviour policies, structure their days — so why should clothing be the exception?\n\nThere is also the practical argument. Teachers in uniform schools report that dress-code disputes consume significant pastoral time in non-uniform institutions. When the rules are clear and universal, there is nothing to argue about, and that time can be redirected to what actually matters: teaching and learning.\n\nNone of this is to say that uniforms are perfect. They can be needlessly expensive (a problem schools should address through affordable suppliers and second-hand schemes), and overly rigid enforcement of minor infractions — untucked shirts, wrong-coloured socks — can indeed feel petty and authoritarian. The solution is sensible policy, not abolition.\n\nSchool uniforms do not crush individuality. They create the conditions in which individuality can flourish — not through what students wear, but through what they learn, question, and become.",
