    question:
      'Starting with this extract, explore how Shakespeare presents the theme of ambition in Macbeth.\n\nExtract (Act 1, Scene 7):\n"I have no spur\nTo prick the sides of my intent, but only\nVaulting ambition, which o\'erleaps itself\nAnd falls on th\' other."\n\nWrite about:\n- how Shakespeare presents ambition in this extract\n- how Shakespeare presents ambition in the play as a whole\n\n[30 marks + 4 marks for AO4]',
    modelAnswer:
      'Shakespeare presents ambition as a destructive, self-defeating force that corrupts moral judgement and ultimately destroys those who succumb to it.\n\nIn this extract, Macbeth is engaged in a soliloquy — a dramatic device Shakespeare uses to reveal his protagonist\'s inner conflict. The equestrian metaphor of "vaulting ambition" is significant: it compares ambition to a horseman who leaps too eagerly and falls on the other side of the saddle. This image captures the paradox at the heart of the play — that excessive ambition defeats its own purpose. The verb "o\'erleaps" suggests ambition as an uncontrolled, impulsive force, while "falls" foreshadows Macbeth\'s own tragic downfall. Importantly, Macbeth recognises this danger intellectually but proves unable to resist it, which is the essence of his tragedy.\n\nThe phrase "I have no spur / To prick the sides of my intent" extends the horse metaphor and reveals Macbeth\'s awareness that he lacks legitimate motivation for regicide. The word "spur" implies that external force is needed to drive him forward — a role Lady Macbeth will soon fulfil. Shakespeare thus presents ambition not as an internal quality alone but as something that requires external catalyst, which complicates a simple reading of Macbeth as inherently evil.\n\nIn the wider play, Shakespeare traces ambition\'s progression from temptation to tyranny. In Act 1, the Witches\' prophecy functions as the initial spark — "All hail, Macbeth, that shalt be king hereafter!" — but Shakespeare is careful to show that the ambition already exists within Macbeth; the Witches merely articulate it. His aside, "Why do I yield to that suggestion / Whose horrid image doth unfix my hair?" reveals that the thought of murder arises spontaneously, suggesting ambition as an innate but suppressed desire.\n\nLady Macbeth\'s ambition operates differently. Where Macbeth hesitates, she acts; where he moralises, she strategises. Her invocation to the spirits — "unsex me here, / And fill me from the crown to the toe top-full / Of direst cruelty" — presents ambition as requiring the suppression of femininity and humanity. Shakespeare suggests that ambition demands the sacrifice of one\'s essential nature, which is ultimately unsustainable — as Lady Macbeth\'s descent into madness demonstrates.\n\nAs the play progresses, Macbeth\'s ambition transforms from aspiration into paranoia. The murder of Banquo — "To be thus is nothing, / But to be safely thus" — shows that ambition has become insatiable. Having achieved the crown, Macbeth discovers that power without security is meaningless, leading to an escalating cycle of violence. Shakespeare presents this as ambition\'s fundamental flaw: it can never be satisfied.\n\nA Jacobean audience would have understood ambition through the lens of the Great Chain of Being and divine right. Macbeth\'s regicide is not merely a crime against Duncan but against God\'s ordained order, which is why nature itself rebels — "darkness does the face of earth entomb." Shakespeare uses pathetic fallacy to present ambition as cosmically destructive, disrupting the natural order itself.\n\nUltimately, Shakespeare presents ambition as tragic because it is inseparable from the qualities that make Macbeth compelling — his imagination, his self-awareness, his capacity for moral reasoning. It is precisely because Macbeth understands the wrongness of his actions that his ambition is so devastating. A lesser mind would not suffer; Macbeth suffers because he knows exactly what he is losing.',
