    difficulty: 3,
    marks: 34,
    timeMinutes: 45,
    question:
      'How does Priestley present ideas about responsibility in An Inspector Calls?\n\nWrite about:\n- the ideas about responsibility in An Inspector Calls\n- how Priestley presents these ideas by the ways he writes\n\n[30 marks + 4 marks for AO4]',
    modelAnswer:
      'Priestley uses An Inspector Calls as a vehicle for his socialist beliefs, presenting responsibility as both a personal moral duty and a collective social obligation. The play argues that the comfortable middle classes have a responsibility to those less fortunate — and that failing in this duty has devastating consequences.\n\nThe Inspector functions as Priestley\'s mouthpiece, delivering the play\'s central message in his final speech: "We are members of one body. We are responsible for each other." The religious allusion to the body of Christ reflects Priestley\'s belief that society is interconnected. The use of the first-person plural "we" is deliberately inclusive, implicating the audience as well as the Birling family. This breaks the fourth wall ideologically, if not literally, making the play\'s message impossible to dismiss as merely fictional.\n\nPriestley structures the play to demonstrate how responsibility is distributed across social classes. Each family member is implicated in Eva Smith\'s death, but their responses reveal their moral character. Mr Birling — "a hard-headed practical man of business" — refuses responsibility entirely, dismissing Eva as merely "a girl of that sort." His language dehumanises her, reducing her to a category rather than an individual. Priestley presents Birling\'s refusal to accept responsibility as both morally repugnant and politically dangerous, linking it to his catastrophically wrong predictions about the Titanic and the impossibility of war.\n\nIn contrast, Sheila accepts responsibility immediately and with genuine emotion: "I felt rotten about it at the time and now I feel a lot worse." Her capacity for guilt demonstrates what Priestley sees as the potential for moral growth in the younger generation. The generational divide is central to Priestley\'s message — the older Birlings represent an entrenched, selfish capitalism that cannot change, while Eric and Sheila represent hope for a more equitable future.\n\nMrs Birling\'s rejection of responsibility is perhaps the most damning. As chair of the Brumley Women\'s Charity Organisation, she had an institutional duty of care to Eva/Daisy. Her refusal to help — because the girl had used the Birling name — reveals the hypocrisy of charitable organisations that serve the self-image of the middle classes rather than the needs of the poor.\n\nPriestley wrote the play in 1945 but set it in 1912, creating dramatic irony that reinforces the theme of responsibility. The audience knows that the characters\' complacency will be shattered by two world wars. Mr Birling\'s confident assertion that war is impossible makes him ridiculous, and by extension makes his rejection of social responsibility seem equally foolish. Priestley implies that the failure to take collective responsibility led directly to the catastrophes of the twentieth century.\n\nThe ambiguous ending — the phone call announcing a real inspector\'s visit — suggests that responsibility cannot be evaded indefinitely. The cyclical structure implies that if society does not learn from its mistakes, it will be forced to confront them again. This was particularly resonant for a 1945 audience rebuilding after war and voting in the Labour government that would create the welfare state.',
