      'Compare how poets present the theme of power in "Ozymandias" by Percy Bysshe Shelley and one other poem from the Power and Conflict anthology.\n\n[30 marks]',
    modelAnswer:
      'Both "Ozymandias" by Shelley and "My Last Duchess" by Browning explore the theme of power, but while Shelley presents power as ultimately transient and futile, Browning presents it as intimate, controlling, and psychologically complex.\n\nShelley\'s sonnet uses the ruined statue of Ozymandias as a symbol of imperial power\'s impermanence. The inscription — "Look on my Works, ye Mighty, and despair!" — is rendered ironic by the "lone and level sands" that surround it. The juxtaposition between the boastful imperative "Look" and the empty desert creates a devastating commentary on human arrogance. Power, Shelley suggests, is an illusion that time inevitably destroys. The choice of sonnet form — traditionally associated with love — is itself ironic, as Shelley uses it to mourn (or celebrate) the death of tyranny.\n\nBrowning\'s dramatic monologue presents a very different kind of power. The Duke\'s power is not political but personal — exerted over his wife and, by extension, over the envoy he addresses. The phrase "I gave commands; / Then all smiles stopped together" reveals power exercised through euphemism and indirection. The chilling vagueness of "commands" — which likely refers to murder — demonstrates how absolute power corrupts language itself, making violence sound administrative.\n\nBoth poets use form to reinforce their themes. Shelley\'s fragmented sonnet — with its unusual rhyme scheme (ABABACDCEDEFEF) — mirrors the broken statue, suggesting that even poetic forms, like empires, resist perfection. Browning\'s use of enjambment in heroic couplets creates a sense of the Duke\'s speech flowing uncontrollably, revealing more than he intends. His power is undermined by his own words — he cannot control his narrative, just as he could not control his wife\'s smiles.\n\nContextually, both poems engage with Romantic-era concerns about authority. Shelley, a radical atheist and republican, uses Ozymandias to critique all forms of autocratic power, including the British Empire. Browning, writing later, examines the psychology of power rather than its politics, anticipating the Victorian fascination with the criminal mind.\n\nUltimately, both poems suggest that power is self-defeating. Ozymandias\'s monument crumbles; the Duke\'s controlled narrative betrays his monstrousness. Power, both poets imply, contains the seeds of its own destruction.',
    markScheme:
      "AO1: Compare ideas (12 marks). AO2: Analyse methods (12 marks). AO3: Context (6 marks). Compare throughout, not sequentially.",
    tips: [
      "Choose a poem that offers a genuine contrast or comparison",
      "Compare methods as well as themes",
      "Integrate contextual knowledge naturally",
      "Structure comparatively — don't write about one poem then the other",
    ],
