    question:
      'How does the writer use language to convey the narrator\'s feelings about their childhood home?\n\n"The kitchen smelled of burnt toast and lavender, a combination that should have been repulsive but instead filled me with a longing so fierce it was almost grief. The wallpaper — faded roses on a cream background — had peeled at the corners, revealing older paper beneath, older patterns, older lives. I ran my fingers along the countertop and felt the familiar groove where my mother had scored a thousand loaves of bread. The house remembered everything I had tried to forget."',
    modelAnswer:
      'The writer uses language to convey a complex mixture of nostalgia, loss, and reluctant emotional connection.\n\nThe olfactory imagery of "burnt toast and lavender" creates an immediate sensory impression that grounds the reader in the domestic space. The juxtaposition of these two contrasting scents — one acrid, one sweet — mirrors the narrator\'s conflicted feelings. The concessive clause "should have been repulsive but instead" signals the narrator\'s surprise at their own emotional response, suggesting they had expected to feel differently upon returning.\n\nThe abstract noun "longing" is intensified by the simile "so fierce it was almost grief," which elevates nostalgia to something physically painful. The adverb "almost" is crucial — it holds the narrator at the boundary between desire and mourning, suggesting the home represents something that is not quite lost but no longer fully accessible.\n\nThe description of the wallpaper functions as a metaphor for layered memory. The verb "revealing" suggests archaeology — each layer of paper representing "older lives" lived in the same space. The tricolon "older paper, older patterns, older lives" creates a rhythmic deepening effect, moving from the physical surface to human experience, implying that the house contains accumulated histories.\n\nThe tactile detail of the "familiar groove" where the narrator\'s mother "scored a thousand loaves" is particularly effective. The verb "scored" carries connotations of marking permanently, and the hyperbolic "thousand" emphasises the repetitive domesticity of the mother\'s life. The groove becomes a physical record of maternal labour.\n\nThe final personification — "The house remembered everything I had tried to forget" — is the most powerful line. It reverses the expected relationship between person and place, giving the house agency and memory while the narrator has been actively suppressing theirs. The contrast between "remembered" and "tried to forget" suggests the impossibility of escaping one\'s past.',
    markScheme:
      "AO2: Explain, comment on and analyse how writers use language, using relevant subject terminology. L4 (7-8): Detailed, perceptive analysis. L3 (5-6): Clear, relevant explanation. L2 (3-4): Some relevant comment. L1 (1-2): Simple awareness.",
