    id: "aqa-lang-p2-q5-02",
    title: "Viewpoint Writing: Social Media and Young People",
    examBoard: "aqa",
    subject: "language",
    topic: "Viewpoint Writing",
    paper: "Paper 2",
    questionNumber: "Q5",
    difficulty: 4,
    marks: 40,
    timeMinutes: 45,
    question:
      '"Social media is destroying the mental health of young people and should be banned for anyone under 16."\n\nWrite a speech to be delivered at a school assembly in which you argue for or against this statement.\n\n(24 marks for content and organisation, 16 marks for technical accuracy)',
    modelAnswer:
      "Good morning. I want to start with a number: three hours and forty-one minutes. That is the average time a British teenager spends on social media every single day. That is over twenty-five hours a week. That is more time than they spend doing homework, playing sport, and talking to their families combined. And if that does not alarm you, I would suggest you are not paying attention.\n\nBut here is what alarms me more than the number itself: the suggestion — increasingly popular among politicians and commentators who really ought to know better — that the solution is simply to ban it. To draw a line at sixteen and declare the problem solved. This is not a policy. It is a fantasy.\n\nLet me be clear. I am not here to defend social media. The evidence linking excessive screen time to anxiety, depression, and disordered eating in young people is robust and growing. The algorithms that govern platforms like TikTok and Instagram are designed — deliberately, mathematically, ruthlessly — to exploit the developing brain's need for validation. This is not a conspiracy theory; it is a business model. And it is doing real harm.\n\nBut a ban would not address this harm. It would simply drive it underground. We know this because we have tried prohibition before — with alcohol, with drugs, with age-restricted content online — and it has never worked. A determined fourteen-year-old with a VPN and a borrowed email address will bypass an age restriction in approximately forty-five seconds. What they will not have, once the ban forces them into unregulated spaces, is any adult oversight whatsoever.\n\nWhat we need instead is education. Not the patronising, once-a-term assembly about cyberbullying that most schools currently offer, but sustained, rigorous digital literacy embedded in the curriculum from primary school onwards. We need to teach young people how algorithms work, how to recognise manipulative design, how to curate their feeds for wellbeing rather than anxiety. We need to give them the tools to navigate the digital world critically, just as we teach them to read books critically.\n\nWe also need regulation — not of users, but of platforms. The Online Safety Act is a start, but it does not go far enough. We should be demanding algorithmic transparency, banning addictive design features aimed at minors, and holding tech executives personally liable when their products cause demonstrable harm. The problem is not that children use social media. The problem is that social media is designed to use them.\n\nFinally, we need honesty. Adults created this technology. Adults profit from it. Adults use it compulsively. To turn around and ban children from it while we scroll through our own feeds is not protection — it is hypocrisy. If we want young people to develop a healthy relationship with technology, we need to model one.\n\nSo no, I do not support a ban. I support something far more difficult and far more effective: taking responsibility. Thank you.",
